This document should be regarded solely as a summary of the contributions from stakeholders. It cannot in any circumstances be regarded as an official position of the European Commission or its services. Responses given as part of the public consultation cannot be considered a representative sample of the views of the EU population.

This factual summary report provides an overview of the input received during the public consultation on the evaluation of the Good Laboratory Practice (GLP) Directives 2004/9/EC and 2004/10/EC. The consultation aimed to gather stakeholder views on the effectiveness, efficiency, relevance, coherence, and EU added value of the current GLP framework. Given the limited number of responses ( 1 ). The consultation was conducted via the 'Have Your Say' portal (2 ), with all contributions submitted electronically. The European Commission performed standard checks to ensure the uniqueness and validity of responses. No responses were discarded, and no organized campaigns were identified.

This summary report is structured to reflect the contributions as received, without interpretation or qualification. It includes basic statistics on participant demographics and a summary of the replies.
1. PARTICIPATION OVERVIEW
The consultation received 11 contributions from a diverse range of stakeholders, including companies, public authorities, business associations, and individual EU citizens. The

( 1 ) Of the 11 contributions received, 10 were submitted through the EU survey platform. One additional response, while prepared using the EU survey template, was submitted via email due to technical difficulties that were resolved after the public consultation deadline.

majority of respondents contributed in English (n=6), followed by Italian (n=2), with single contributions in Spanish, Portuguese, and Romanian.

In terms of stakeholder groups, 5 out of 11 respondents (45%) were companies, followed by public authorities (n=3, or 27%), business associations (n=2, or 18%), and other stakeholders (n=1, or 9%). No replies have been received by citizens. Geographically, 9 out of 11 respondents (82%) were from EU countries, while 2 respondents (18%) were from non-EU countries. 2. SUMMARY OF CONTRIBUTIONS
The survey aimed to gather information on the perceived benefits and drawbacks of the GLP Directives, as well as their impact on various stakeholders. Specifically:

• Ensuring quality, integrity, and reliability: 6 out of 11 respondents replied that the GLP Directives ensure the quality, integrity, and reliability of non-clinical safety tests to a very large extent. The remaining 5 out of 11 replied to a large extent.
  • Mutual recognition of data: 5 out of 11 respondents indicated that mutual recognition of data through the GLP principles has saved time and economic resources within their organisation to a very large extent, while 4 out of 11 indicated to a large extent and the remaining 2 to a moderate extent.
  • Contribution of the GLP Directives: the respondents stated that the GLP Directives have contributed to:

â€¢ Scope and adequacy: 8 out of 11 respondents believe that the scope of the Directives is adequate. In particular, 3 respondents affirming their adequacy, stated that they are adequate, still relevant, or that the principles of good practice are clear and appropriate. Another respondent mentioned that the scope is adequate as it is

applied through specific product norms. One respondent noted that the Directives ensure reliable, traceable, and reproducible safety studies, which is essential for protecting human health and the environment. Then, 2 respondents suggested that the Directives could be improved, with 1 recommending that they be more detailed with examples, and 1 stating that certain criteria do not influence quality and more inspection is needed. Additionally, 1 respondent commented on inconsistent application of the Directives across states, citing insufficient harmonisation. Finally, 1 respondent highlighted the importance of ensuring proper implementation of GLP in regulatory contexts to prevent the misuse of new or nonvalidated methods.

• Administrative burden: when investigating how burdensome are some obligations and activities related to complying with the GLP Directives, the respondents provided the following feedback:
    • o Maintaining administrative and office records related to GLP compliance: very burdensome for 2 out 6 respondents, to a moderate extend for 2 out of 6 respondents and somewhat burdensome for the remaining 2 respondents.
    • o Preparing technical dossiers for GLP studies (e.g., for regulatory submission): to a moderate extend for 4 out of 6 respondents and somewhat burdensome for the remaining 2 respondents.
    • o Submitting reports, data, and statistics to competent authorities: to a moderate extend for 4 out of 9 respondents, somewhat burdensome for 4 other respondents and not at all burdensome for the remaining respondent.
    • o Documenting and labelling GLP-compliant studies: very burdensome for 2 out 6 respondents, to a moderate extend for 2 out of 6 respondents and somewhat burdensome for the remaining 2 respondents.
    • o Record keeping related to GLP compliance (e.g., QA records, study protocols): very burdensome for 3 out 10 respondents, to a moderate extend for 4 out of 10 respondents, somewhat burdensome for the remaining 2 respondents and not at all burdensome for the remaining respondent.
    • o Coordinating with OECD partners for mutual acceptance of data (MAD): half of the 6 respondents replied to a moderate extent burdensome, while the other half somewhat burdensome.
    • o Designing and conducting GLP-compliant studies: similarly to the previous question, half of the 6 respondents replied to a moderate extent burdensome, while the other half somewhat burdensome.
    • o Training personnel on GLP compliance requirements: one responded very burdensome, 2 to a moderate extent burdensome and another person replied somewhat burdensome.
    • o Implementing internal quality assurance and compliance systems: half of the 6 respondents replied to a moderate extent burdensome, while the other half somewhat burdensome

• o Collaborating with monitoring authorities during inspections: there is a lack of consensus on this reply as one respondent indicated this element to be very burdensome and 2 indicated to a moderate extent burdensome, while other respondents replied somewhat burdensome (n=2) or not at all (n=1).
  • o Developing and maintaining compliance tracking systems: two replies selected for this point. One respondent indicating that the systems are somewhat burdensome, while another to a moderate extend burdensome.
  • o Taking corrective actions to address GLP non-compliance: two replies were received concurred that taking corrective actions is somewhat burdensome.
  • o Re-inspections for non-compliance (including follow-up inspections): one respondent indicated that this is to a moderate extend burdensome, while another indicated not at all.
  • EU added value: on the questions asking whether the objectives of the GLP Directives are better achieved when implemented at the EU level, rather than at the individual national level, more than half of the respondents (from 64% to 82%) recognised the EU added value. In particular, when indicating a higher level of protecting human and environmental safety (8 out 11 respondents), ensuring trust and confidence in certain products (9 out 11 respondents), reducing trade barriers and costs in the internal market (8 out 11 respondents), monitoring compliance (9 out 11 respondents), handling suspicions of non-compliance (8 out 11 respondents), preventing fraudulent practices (7 out 11 respondents), ensuring high-quality and valid data for safety testing of test items contained in pharmaceutical, pesticide, or cosmetic products, veterinary drugs as well as food and feed additives, and industrial chemicals (9 out 11 respondents), standardising data requirements to avoid double testing (8 out 11 respondents), and harmonising rules for inspection and audit (9 out 11 respondents). One respondent added that it is important to ensure the proper implementation of GLP in various regulatory contexts in order to avoid the inappropriate use of new methods or non-validated methods for aspects that require regularity. The respondent added that GLP also ensures establishing robust comparisons and/or justifications (from both a scientific and regulatory perspective) that do not provoke debate/controversial interpretation.
  • Sectoral impact in case of withdrawal of the Directives: according to the respondent, the sector would be affected if the Directives were repealed very negatively; especially in terms of barriers to trade (4 out 11; while 6 out of 11 replied negatively and one respondent mentioned no impact); of regulatory burden (6 out of 11; while 5 out of 11 replied negatively); of quality of test data (7 out of 11; while 4 replied "negatively"); of assessment of hazards (6 out of 11; 2 out of 11 replied negatively and 2 replied no impact). The potential repeal of the GLP Directives has sparked additional concerns: 4 respondents noted that the Directives have reached their objectives, remain relevant, and continue to help organisations meet customer requirements and respond to stakeholder needs. 1 respondent raised concerns about the challenges and costs associated with implementing and maintaining GLP compliance, including the significant investment required for digitalisation, personnel training, and procedure adaptation. 1 respondent pointed out that the Directives may not be fully aligned with current developments, such as new OECD guidelines, advisory documents, and emerging technologies like

artificial intelligence. 1 respondent noted that well-performed academic studies may not always be GLP compliant due to certain demanding requirements. Additionally, 1 respondent mentioned that it is very expensive to maintain GLP compliance. Overall, the comments suggest that while the GLP Directives have been effective in achieving their objectives, there may be areas where they could be improved or updated to reflect changing stakeholders' needs and technological advancements.

• When asking for which sectors they require or provide GLP-compliant studies, out of the 11 replies received, the most common sectors are Industrial chemicals (8 responses), Pesticides/Biocides (7 responses), and Cosmetics (5 responses), followed by Food and feed additives (4 responses), Pharmaceutical (5 responses), and Laboratory service provider (3 responses), while EU agency, National GLP Monitoring authority, National GLP Regulatory authority, and Other accounted for 2 responses or less.
  • Finally, when asked to specify the areas of expertise you require or offer; out of the 11 respondents the distribution is the following: Analytical and clinical chemistry testing: 9 responses ;Environmental toxicity studies on aquatic and terrestrial organisms: 8 responses; Physical-chemical testing: 11 responses; Mutagenicity studies: 6 responses; Residue studies: 7 responses; Studies on behaviour in water, soil and air; bioaccumulation: 8 responses; Studies on effects on mesocosms and natural ecosystems: 5 responses; Toxicity studies: 6 responses; Other: 2 responses.
Sectors and Expertise

The respondents represent various sectors, including cosmetics, food and feed additives, industrial chemicals, pesticides/biocides, pharmaceuticals, and veterinary drugs. The areas of expertise required or offered include analytical and clinical chemistry testing, environmental toxicity studies, physical-chemical testing, residue studies, and toxicity studies.
Sector specific views
Despite the limited number of respondents from industry, some specific views could be delineated from the responses received. In particular:

• Industrial chemicals and Pesticides: respondents from these sectors emphasized the critical role of GLP in ensuring the safety and efficacy of chemical products. However, they also pointed to delays in the approval process for new testing methods, which can hinder innovation.
  • Cosmetics and Food additives: stakeholders in these areas indicated the importance of GLP in supporting consumer safety but noted that the current framework could be more adaptive to the specific needs of these sectors.
  • Public authorities: contributions from public authorities focused on the need for robust enforcement mechanisms to prevent non-compliance. They also suggested that greater resources should be allocated to support national competent authorities in their oversight roles.
